Install required packages

tidyverse for data import and wrangling

lubridate for date functions

ggplot for visualization

library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
library(ggplot2)

##Import datasets and create merged df:

library(readr)
#Download 12 months of data:
#Method to download, unzip and create df directly from aws found here: https://intellipaat.com/community/11398/using-r-to-download-zipped-data-file-extract-and-import-data
#Create a temporary file to store the file to be downloaded:
temp <- tempfile()
#Download the file from the url:
download.file("https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/202106-divvy-tripdata.zip",temp)
#To extract the file from temp file and read the data using read.csv:
data202106 <- read.csv(unz(temp, "202106-divvy-tripdata.csv"))
#Remove the temporary file:
unlink(temp)

#Merge 12 monthly datasets into one using rbind():

cyclist_data202007_202106 <- rbind(data202007, data202008, data202009, data202010, data202011, data202012, data202101, data202102, data202103, data202104, data202105, data202106)

##Data Cleaning

#Rename columns for clarity:
clean_cyclist_data202007_202106 <- cyclist_data202007_202106 %>%
  rename(user_type = member_casual) %>%
  rename(bike_type=rideable_type) %>%
  rename(start_time=started_at) %>%
  rename(end_time=ended_at) 

# Remove lat and long fields 
clean_cyclist_data202007_202106 <- clean_cyclist_data202007_202106 %>%  
  select(-c(start_lat, start_lng, end_lat, end_lng))
#Convert Date/Time from char to POSIXit using function strptime()

# Add columns that list the date, month, day, and year of each ride
clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$date <- as.Date(clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$start_time) #The default format is yyyy-mm-dd
clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$month <- format(as.Date(clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$date), "%m")
clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$day <- format(as.Date(clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$date), "%d")
clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$year <- format(as.Date(clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$date), "%Y")
clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$day_of_week <- format(as.Date(clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$date), "%A")
#Calculate ride duration in new column:
mutate(clean_cyclist_data202007_202106, ride_duration = ymd_hms(end_time)-ymd_hms(start_time))
max(clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$ride_duration)

# Remove "bad" data
# Removed entries when bikes started or ended at Hubbard Bike-checking station (maintenance), ride_length <5 sec, removed rides that were missing starting or ending station.
# Create a new version of the dataframe (v2) since data is being removed (took data from 4,460,151 rows to 4,137,516 rows)
v2_clean_cyclist_data202007_202106 <- clean_cyclist_data202007_202106[!(clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$ride_duration<5  | clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$start_station_id == "Hubbard Bike-checking (LBS-WH-TEST)" | clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$end_station_id == "Hubbard Bike-checking (LBS-WH-TEST)" | clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$end_station_id == "" | clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$start_station_id == "" | clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$start_station_name == "HUBBARD ST BIKE CHECKING (LBS-WH-TEST)" | clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$end_station_name == "HUBBARD ST BIKE CHECKING (LBS-WH-TEST)"),]

# Let's visualize the number of rides by rider type
v2_clean_cyclist_data202007_202106 %>% 
  mutate(weekday = wday(start_time, label = TRUE)) %>% 
  group_by(user_type, weekday) %>% 
  summarise(number_of_rides = n()
            ,average_duration = mean(ride_duration)) %>% 
  arrange(user_type, weekday)  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = weekday, y = number_of_rides, fill = user_type)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge")
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'user_type'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

# Analyze data by user type and weekday
v2_clean_cyclist_data202007_202106 %>% 
  mutate(weekday = wday(start_time, label = TRUE)) %>%  #creates weekday field using wday()
  group_by(user_type, weekday) %>%  #groups by usertype and weekday
  summarise(number_of_rides = n()                           #calculates the number of rides and average duration 
  ,average_duration = mean(ride_duration)) %>%      # calculates the average duration
  arrange(user_type, weekday)                               # sorts
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'user_type'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
# Let's create a visualization for average duration
v2_clean_cyclist_data202007_202106%>% 
  mutate(weekday = wday(start_time, label = TRUE)) %>% 
  group_by(user_type, weekday) %>% 
  summarise(number_of_rides = n()
            ,average_duration = mean(ride_duration)) %>% 
  arrange(user_type, weekday)  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = weekday, y = average_duration, fill = user_type)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge")
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'user_type'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

counts <- aggregate(v2_clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$ride_duration ~ v2_clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$user_type + v2_clean_cyclist_data202007_202106$day_of_week, FUN = mean)
write.csv(counts, file = '~/Desktop/avg_ride_length.csv')
